**Hey everyone!** I’m going to be participating in Hyperscale development, community and investment parts more. So nice to meet everyone here.

I have some feedback regarding the new landing page that I believe is required to be fixed before the launch. Don't want to be negative, but we should have a high bar in terms of everything.

**Functionality**:
The main thing is it’s not very clear from the landing page why should I care and why should I apply as a DAO. 

- Let’s include a Knowledge base link on the top - it’s going to be a link to our notion where there is going to be FAQ, all necessary information that I’m going to work through.
- I’d change most of the texts. Let's create a figma file for that. Potentially the vision part should be not a separate part in the end but it should be the landing page itself, meaning all the titles, articulation should lead to what the vision is.

**Design**:
- Texts, colors are in low resolution in some places, because of that if feels like a big PDF file that someone has put on a custom domain. (If you check https://rebrand.hyperscalefund.com/section1/bg.svg it actually shows as a low resolution background image as well).
- I’d use css instead of images, here https://rebrand.hyperscalefund.com/section2/card1.svg
- I see small white stripes on both sides of a page inside of safari
- illustrations do not make sense with the titles
- design in general could be much better, I even don’t say about animations right now. The previous version looked better.

We chose these sites https://discord.com/channels/916751469678579784/928558777811214336/931969420199329812 as our inspiration because they are at the forefront of modern design and they have a fun collaborative vibe. Since web3 = cutting edge + fun vibe ---> we felt it was a good visual style. 

However, we are open to trying a new style. The first step would be to get a bunch of example inspiration (a palette of ideas/styles) and then have leadership make a final decision on which inspiration we want to set the direction. Then we can explore in that direction until we have something we like.

I'd say, design team, core, general public can submit link in a Design channel / thread links to inspiration. The we all vote it with thumbs up, thumbs down. The best designs are short listed and tried in form of a MVP sphere like looking page...

Design by committee (deciding on the style by voting) is not an ideal approach, however, I agree voting can be a good input into what leadership ultimately decides.

An analogy would be deciding on an engine design for a car by having a group of non engineers vote between types (v8, straight 4, turbine, electric, etc) for a car you are building. Maybe the RX-7 turbine engine is a popular idea at the time. However, it would be a bad choice for the car that is being built. You wouldn't want to have a turbine engine chose just because it is popular.

Engineering and design decisions should't be based on what's popular among novices. It should be decided by a small set of experts.
